node.text:
Did you know you can use essential oils to help naturally balance your hormones?⁠
⁠
Here are a few of the essential oils I recommend friends and family use ⬇️⁠
⁠
Clary sage’s biggest benefit is that it helps balance estrogen in the body. If you have infertility or estrogen-induced cancer, clary sage helps balance your estrogen levels and hormones. ⁠
⁠
Thyme oil benefits the body by producing more progesterone, which helps balance the body’s hormones. ⁠
⁠
And, sandalwood oil helps balance testosterone levels in both men and women. ⁠
⁠
Want to learn more ways to naturally balance your hormones? Head over to my stories and swipe up.

node.title: Balance Hormones Naturally With Essential Oils⁠

You’ve probably used the phrases: “I have butterflies in my stomach,” “I have a gut feeling about this,” or “there’s a pit in my stomach.” ⁠
⁠
Have you ever wondered why so many of these sayings involve our brains and gut? ⁠
⁠
The answer is the gut-brain connection.⁠
⁠
Let's dive into how this connection works and how it impacts your health.⁠
⁠
To learn more about the gut-brain connection head to my stories and swipe up.

Water is vital for overall health and should be your No. 1 beverage choice; however, your body needs electrolytes for proper hydration. ⁠
⁠
These seven foods are high in electrolytes and will help your body stay hydrated! ⁠
⁠
One way I like to incorporate these foods into my diet is with a smoothie made with greens, fruit and coconut milk or with a big salad of mixed greens topped with chopped veggies, avocado and a protein. ⁠
⁠

Want a full list of the best hydrating foods? Head to my stories and swipe up!⁠

Each individual's gut is influenced by factors including their diet, genetics, use of medications, stress levels and environment. ⁠
⁠
This means that what’s best for one person in terms of gut health may be a big problem for another.⁠
⁠
Today, I’m going to break down some of the most common gut-health myths so that you can support your gut more effectively.

One of the simplest ways to maintain health, both physically and mentally, is to get enough sleep.⁠
⁠
And with a stress-filled world and life, falling asleep, and staying asleep, can be a real challenge.⁠
⁠
If you know something needs to change, try taking a look at your diet. What we eat affects so much more than just our stomachs. ⁠
⁠
Try incorporating these foods into your diet for a better night's sleep ⬇️⁠
⁠
▪️ Walnut and almonds are great sources of tryptophan, which is the amino acid that produces serotonin and melatonin⁠
⁠
▪️ Bananas, kiwis, and especially tart cherries naturally increase melatonin production which can be beneficial to getting a good night's rest.⁠
⁠
▪️ Kale, as well as spinach, Swiss chard and collard greens, often offer magnesium which can help enhance sleep quality.⁠
⁠

Craving Italian? Try my eggplant rollatini recipe! ⁠
⁠
Not only is this recipe a favorite in my household, but it is also loaded with riboflavin (vitamin B2) which helps turn the food you eat into energy to function. ⁠
⁠
What you'll need for this recipe: ⁠
2 large eggplants, sliced lengthwise⁠
½ teaspoon sea salt⁠
½ teaspoon black pepper⁠
1–1½ cups marinara sauce⁠
2 large eggs⁠
3 cups spinach⁠
1 package goat feta (4 ounces)⁠
1 teaspoon dried oregano⁠
1 teaspoon parsley⁠
1 teaspoon dried basil⁠
2 cups pecorino romano, grated⁠
1 cup raw sheep cheese, grated⁠
⁠
For the full recipe, head to my stories and swipe up!

Wondering what endocrine disruptors are? ⁠
⁠
Endocrine disruptors are chemicals that may interfere with the body’s endocrine system and produce adverse developmental, reproductive, neurological and immune effects in both humans and wildlife. ⁠
⁠
The damage is believed to be most severe during prenatal or early pregnancy exposure. ⁠
⁠
Head to my stories to see which household products contain these dangerous chemicals, and how you can avoid them.

Did you know that there are over a hundred herbs and spices that can be consumed or used topically for healing?⁠⁠
⁠⁠
These natural foods work to reduce inflammation, boost your immune system, and much more. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
For example, thyme is a source of vitamin C, vitamin A, iron, manganese and calcium. It can be used to boost your mood, relieve respiratory conditions like sore throat and bronchitis and lower blood pressure.⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Sage has been used medically for thousands of years. It can improve your memory and concentration, fight free radicals and so much more. ⁠⁠
⁠⁠
I always recommend adding at least one fresh herb to your meals when you're cooking, but the more the merrier!⁠⁠
⁠⁠
Want to learn more? I'm sharing 101 herbs & spices, their benefits, and recipes to incorporate them into your life on my stories.

Hormonal balance is one of the most important aspects of a properly functioning body. ⁠
⁠
Some of the most common side effects of hormone imbalance include infertility, weight gain, depression and more. ⁠
⁠
One of the best ways to balance hormones naturally is with your diet. Here are a few simple changes you can make ⬇️⁠
⁠
1️⃣ Swap carbs for healthy fats⁠
⁠
Healthy fats, like coconut oil, avocados and salmon, have the opposite effect of refined carbohydrates, which lead to inflammation and can mess with the balance of your hormones. ⁠
⁠
2️⃣ Supplement to fill nutritional voids⁠
⁠
While a healthy diet is key for all aspects of health, it's sometimes necessary to supplement in order to fill nutritional voids that can be leading to hormonal imbalance. ⁠
⁠
3️⃣ Use certain essential oils ⁠
⁠
Clary sage, fennel, lavender, sandalwood and thyme are all great essential oils that can be used to help balance your hormones. ⁠
⁠
